    "占驗古人": "The Herdsboy Rides a Calf Home / Alternative: The Imperial Uncle Encounters Shui-ging (牧童跨犢回歸 / 皇叔遇水鏡)",
    "籤文": "The evening sun returns upon the backs of the crows on the horizon, the children beyond the mound ride their calves home. / The Qiang (Western) flute is played frequently, the sound is clear and penetrating; what joy is contained in its varying tunes?",
    "背景故事": "As the sun sets over the hill, the crows on the horizon return to their nests. The herdsboys beyond the cultivated land ride their calves home, their bamboo flutes filling the air with melodious, joyful tunes. / *Modern Interpretation:* This refers to the banquet held by Choi Mau in Xiangyang, where he intended to assassinate **Lau Bei** (Lau Bei). **Lau Bei**, sensing the danger, escaped during the banquet, riding his horse 'Dilu' across the river to safety. As the sun was setting, he was guided by a herdsboy and was fortunate to meet the hermit Master Shui-ging (**Szema Fai**), who subsequently introduced him to **Chui Shu**, **Chu-kot Leung** (Chu-kot Leung), and **Pong Tung**, a group of wise men who would contend for control of the land. The Verses state: *Evening sun and Qiang flute, herdsboys ride their calves, a benefactor's guidance, a better tomorrow.* The Quatrain offers: *Many heroes contend for the Three Kingdoms, Lau Bei and Szema Fai meet by chance.* / This lot is a scene of joy; all matters are stable and without impediment. No need for worry.",
    "詳情": "Fame and Wealth will be achieved later in time. The late season is superior for sericulture. Marriage may be compatible. Pregnancy is without alarm. Peace and safety are assured for illness. Travellers will return. Aspirations are agreeable to the heart. Fung Shui is stable and without impediment. Lost Items may be recovered upon careful searching. Personal Fortune is of peace, safety, and no illness. Weather/Timing is clear and moderate, agreeable to human sentiment. The conclusion will be felicitous for travel."
